# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1871-spanish-general-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] General elections to the special Cortes of Cádiz were held in Spain in 1810.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 276 seats in the Cortes of Cádiz – which served as a parliamentary Regency after Ferdinand VII was deposed by Napoleon.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] During the first years of the Spanish War of Independence (1808-1814) the popular revolts of the Spanish people were accompanied by the creation of provincial and local defense "Juntas".
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] Those juntas assumed national sovereignty, forming their own local and regional governing bodies.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] These juntas aimed to defend against the French invasion and fill the power vacuum, refusing to recognize José I Bonaparte as their legitimate king.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] The juntas were mainly composed of military personnel, representatives of the high clergy, officials and professors.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] In September 1808 the local and provincial juntas ceded their power to the Supreme Central Government Junta of the Kingdom, which led the war against the French and was recognized as the legitimate government of Spain by the United Kingdom and other anti-Napoleonic countries.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] The Supreme Junta summoned an extraordinary meeting of the Cortes of Cádiz, a revolutionary act, since the right to call for a meeting of the Cortes was exclusive to the crown.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] After an intense debate in the Supreme Junta it was decided that the Cortes of Cádiz would be unicameral, elected by census suffrage (only those with a certain level of income could vote) and indirect.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] The Cortes met for the first time in the last major Spanish foothold during the Peninsular War, Cádiz, on the Isla de León, on September 24, 1810.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] A majority voting system was used for the election, with 32 multi-member constituencies and 2 single-member constituencies.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1810-spanish-general-election] All male citizens above 25 years old could vote or be voted.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1813-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in 1813.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1813-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 149 seats in the Congress of Deputies.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1813-spanish-general-election] The 1813 elections were the first ones held since the approval of the 1812 Cádiz Constitution.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1813-spanish-general-election] All males over 21 years old, a total of 3,216,460 people, had the right to vote.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in 1820.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 203 seats in the Congress of Deputies.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] The 1820 elections were the first ones since the 1820 revolution.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] The elections were held under the Spanish Constitution of 1812.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] A majority voting system was used for the election, with 33 multi-member constituencies and various single-member ones.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1820-spanish-general-election] Most MPs were liberals, mainly from the *moderate* (or *doceañista*) faction.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1822-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in 1822.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1822-spanish-general-election] The 1822 elections were the second ones since the 1820 revolution.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1822-spanish-general-election] 3,215,460 people were eligible to vote (universal male suffrage), out of a population of 11,661,865.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1822-spanish-general-election] Almost all MPs were liberals, mainly from the radical *veinteañista* or *exaltada* faction.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in 1834.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 188 seats in the Congress of Deputies.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] The 1834 elections were the first ones since 1822 and signalled the return of liberalism to Spain after the absolutist Década Ominosa.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] The elections were held under the Spanish Royal Statute of 1834, not under a full constitutional system.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] A first-past-the-post system was used with 48 multi-member constituencies and one single-member constituency.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1834-spanish-general-election] Only around 18,000 people were allowed to vote, out of a population of 12 million.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1837-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in November 1837.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1837-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 241 seats in the Congress of Deputies.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1837-spanish-general-election] Restricted census suffrage, only 262,000 people out of a total population of 12,162,872 were allowed to vote.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1837-spanish-general-election] The elections were held on 22 September, at the peak of the First Carlist War.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1837-spanish-general-election] A majority voting system was used for the election, with 51 multi-member constituencies and 1 single-member constituency.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1839-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain on 24 July 1839.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1839-spanish-general-election] Restricted census suffrage, only 376,255 people out of a total population of 12,162,872 were allowed to vote.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1839-spanish-general-election] A majority voting system was used for the election, with 48 multi-member constituencies and 1 single-member constituency.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] A general election was held in Spain from 8 to 11 March 1871 to elect the members of the 1st Cortes under the Spanish Constitution of 1869, during the Democratic Sexennium period.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] 406 of 424 seats in the Congress of Deputies and all 200 seats in the Senate were up for election.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] In the Canary Islands the election was held until 15 March, in Puerto Rico it was held from 20 to 23 June, and in Cuba it was indefinitely postponed.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] The election was held following the promulgation of the 1869 Constitution and the swearing-in of Amadeo I as King of Spain on 2 January 1871.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] Francisco Serrano, a member of the Liberal Union (part of the ruling Monarchist–Democratic Coalition together with the Progressive Party and the *Cimbrios* Democrats), was the prime minister before the election.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] Prince Amadeo of Savoy was chosen as new King of Spain on 16 November 1870 and sworn-in as Amadeo I on 2 January 1871, but Prim's assassination on 27 December left Amadeo without his proponent and main supporter.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] A new coalition cabinet formed by the Liberal Union, the Progressive Party and the *Cimbrios* Democrats was formed by Serrano, who called a snap election as a show of legitimacy for the new monarch, whose foreign origins made him unpopular with the general populace.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] In order to ensure the victory of the Monarchist–Democratic Coalition, Serrano reinstated first-past-the-post voting, which made it easier for the government to use electoral fraud in rural districts.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] Voters were required to present an "electoral card" (*cédula electoral*) that mayors were entitled to award to its constituents; as most of these were aligned with the governing coalition, they could refuse awarding the card to voters that were hostile to the government.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] They also employed voter intimidation tactics through the *partida de la porra* aligned to the Progressive Party, to violently attack opponents.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] For Carlists, the good results obtained on the previous election, coupled with the failure of uprising attempts in the summers of 1869 and 1870 (the latter known as *la escocada*), led to the movement favouring electoral means to achieve power.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] Ramón Cabrera, *de facto* leader of the movement, resigned as captain general of the Royal Carlist Army and retired from politics due to disagreements with Carlos de Borbón.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] The pretender assumed the chieftainship of the party and named a Central Council presided by the Marquis of Villadarias, who organised electoral activity and propaganda.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] Under the 1869 Constitution, the Spanish Cortes were conceived as "co-legislative bodies", forming a nearly perfect bicameral system.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] The term of each chamber of the Cortes—the Congress and one-quarter of the Senate—expired three years from the date of their previous election, unless they were dissolved earlier.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] Election day was held over several voting days: the first was used to elect polling station officials, and the remaining ones were devoted to the parliamentary election itself.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] The monarch had the prerogative to dissolve both chambers at any given time—either jointly or separately—and call a snap election.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] Only elections to renew one-quarter of the Senate were constitutionally required to be held concurrently with elections to the Congress, though the former could be renewed in its entirety in the case that a full dissolution was agreed by the monarch.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] The Cortes had been officially dissolved since 2 January 1871, following the swearing-in of Amadeo I as King of Spain.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] The election decree was issued on 14 February, setting election day to start on 8 March (extended until 15 March in the Canary Islands) and scheduling for both chambers to reconvene on 3 April.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] The publication of the corresponding decree for Puerto Rico was delayed until 1 April, setting election day in the island for between 20 and 23 June.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] In Cuba, elections were indefinitely postponed due to the Ten Years' War.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] Voting for each chamber of the Cortes was based on universal manhood suffrage, comprising all Spanish national males over 25 years of age with full civil rights.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] In Puerto Rico, voting was based on censitary suffrage, comprising Spanish males of voting age who were either literate or taxpayers with a minimum quota of 16 escudos in direct taxes.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] Additional restrictions excluded those deprived of political rights or barred from public office by a final sentence, criminally imprisoned (without bail) or convicted, and homeless.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] The Congress of Deputies had one seat per 40,000 inhabitants or fraction above 20,000.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] All were elected in single-member districts using plurality voting and distributed among the provinces of Spain according to population.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] Cuba and Puerto Rico were allocated 18 and 15 seats, respectively.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] As a result of the aforementioned allocation, 424 single-member districts were established.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] All 200 Senate seats were elected using indirect, two-round majority voting.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] Delegates chosen by local councils—each of which was assigned an initial minimum of one delegate, with one additional delegate for every six councillors—voted for senators together with provincial deputies.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] Provinces and the whole of Puerto Rico were allocated four seats each.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] For the Congress, the law provided for by-elections to fill vacant seats during the legislative term.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] For the Senate, any vacancies arising during the legislative term were filled in the chamber's next full or one-quarter election, with senators elected this way serving the remainder of their seat's original term.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] For the Congress, Spanish males with the right to vote could run for election.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] Ineligibility provisions for both chambers also applied to a number of territorial officials within their areas of jurisdiction or relevant territories, during their term of office and up to three months afterwards; public contractors; tax collectors; and public debtors.
[src:1871-spanish-general-election/1871-spanish-general-election] Additionally in Puerto Rico, ineligibility extended to those convicted of slave trade crimes.
